index 688cc0e7..04908c2c 100644
--- a/BUGS
+++ b/BUGS
@@ -1,16 +1,20 @@
-- assign-cmdsubst-value-loses-escaping: a variable assignment whose RHS
-  is a command substitution containing a literal backslash loses one
-  level of backslash escaping (`X=$(echo 'a\\b'); echo "$X"` prints
-  "a\b" instead of "a\\b"). The assignment's own "name=" text is
-  literal source (parser-doubled for glob protection) sharing the same
-  argument buffer as the substituted value (which was never doubled),
-  and only one expand_unescape() pass runs over the whole buffer --
-  confirmed present before and after fixes/69 (that fix only handles a
-  word that's *purely* a substitution, not one mixing a literal prefix
-  with substituted content in the same buffer). Needs per-fragment
-  unescape tracking instead of one flag per assembled argument node;
-  see fixes/69's patch comment in expand_arg.c for the mechanism this
-  would extend.
+- heredoc-body-loses-escaping: a here-document body loses one level of
+  backslash escaping before whatever reads it ever sees it -- `cat
+  <<'EOF'` / `a\\b` / `EOF` delivers "a\b" (one backslash) on the pipe,
+  confirmed via `od -c` on the receiving end, not just in how it's
+  later displayed. The delimiter is quoted (`<<'EOF'`), so this isn't
+  parameter/command/arithmetic expansion or backslash-newline line
+  splicing stripping it (those are the only two things POSIX allows a
+  quoted-delimiter here-doc body to undergo) -- the body's literal
+  bytes are wrong before any of that logic could even run. Found while
+  verifying fixes/70; confirmed unaffected by that fix (a different
+  subsystem: heredoc content storage/delivery in src/redir/, not
+  argument expansion), so still open.
+
+    cat <<'EOF' | od -c
+    a\\b
+    EOF
+    # prints "a \ b \n" (one backslash) -- should be "a \ \ b \n" (two)
 
